WEBVTT

00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.620
The objective of PyAnalySeries is to provide an application with

00:00:03.620 --> 00:00:09.400
interactive capabilities to explore 2D time-series efficiently and to perform

00:00:09.400 --> 00:00:14.430
computations on the data, in particular interpolation between series.

00:00:14.430 --> 00:00:17.910
The first step is to visualize a series so let’s

00:00:17.910 --> 00:00:18.710
see how.

00:00:18.710 --> 00:00:21.850
From the main window, users can display a series by

00:00:21.850 --> 00:00:23.820
pressing Control D.

00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:28.280
The Display window then opens, organized into multiple tabs.

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:33.210
The application also allows the visualization of multiple series simultaneously

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:35.590
which will be introduced later.

00:00:35.590 --> 00:00:39.680
For now, select a series and press Control D to

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:41.200
open the Display window.

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:43.960
Users can zoom in and out using the mouse wheel

00:00:44.010 --> 00:00:47.560
or trackpad, and pan across the data by holding the

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:49.540
right mouse button.

00:00:49.540 --> 00:00:53.200
Zooming and panning can be applied independently to each axis

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:57.250
by positioning the cursor over the corresponding axis or applied

00:00:57.250 --> 00:01:00.950
to both axes simultaneously when the cursor is over the

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:02.180
plot area.

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:06.010
Axis representation can be modified at any time.

00:01:06.010 --> 00:01:09.360
You can invert an axis … switch to a logarithmic

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:13.700
scale when appropriate … and return to a linear scale

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:17.860
These transformations are available for each axis through the context

00:01:17.860 --> 00:01:20.950
menu, accessed with the right mouse button.

00:01:20.950 --> 00:01:23.990
Axis limits can also be adjusted dynamically.

00:01:23.990 --> 00:01:27.650
For both axes, users may choose between a local autoscaling

00:01:27.990 --> 00:01:32.360
adapted to the current view or a global autoscaling applied

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:34.400
to the entire dataset.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:38.220
These settings can be defined independently for each axis.

00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:40.780
When the cursor is over the plot area and not

00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:45.330
on the axes a global autoscaling affecting both axes is

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:47.800
available from the context menu.

00:01:47.800 --> 00:01:50.900
Data points can be displayed by pressing the Control key

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:54.550
allowing precise inspection of values along the curve.

00:01:54.550 --> 00:01:58.320
Export functionality is accessible through the context menu.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:02.000
Users can generate figures in standard formats such as PNG

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.390
or PDF ensuring compatibility with publications and presentations.

00:02:07.390 --> 00:02:10.950
The Data tab provides access to raw values and allows

00:02:10.990 --> 00:02:15.280
easy copying into a spreadsheet using standard shortcuts such as

00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:18.080
Control C and Control V.

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:21.270
The Stat tab presents computed statistics.

00:02:21.270 --> 00:02:25.610
And finally, the Info tab displays the processing history and

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:27.990
allows users to add comments.

00:02:27.990 --> 00:02:30.740
You can close the window at any time using the

00:02:30.740 --> 00:02:32.930
standard shortcut Control W.
